    {
      "question": "If a quadrilateral $ABCD$ circumscribes a circle, prove that $AB + CD = AD + BC$.",
      "answer": "Proof based on tangent properties",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the theorem that tangents drawn from an external point to a circle are equal in length.",
          "Label the points of contact and equate the segments of the sides to prove the sum of opposite sides are equal."
        ],
        "derivation": "AP = AS, BP = BQ, CQ = CR, DR = DS \\\\ AB+CD = (AP+PB) + (CR+RD) = (AS+BQ) + (CQ+DS) = (AS+DS) + (BQ+CQ) = AD+BC"
      },
